 Description:
 The Ground/Air Task Oriented Radar (G/ATOR) is a critical Commandant of the Marine Corps Force Design program. G/ATOR is a multi-role, ground-based, expeditionary 3D radar system employed by both the
 Air Combat Element and Ground Combat Element within the Marine Air Ground Task Force. It satisfies the Marine Air Command and Control System and the Ground Counter Fire/Counter Battery capabilities. G/
 ATOR provides mobile, multi-functional, three-dimensional surveillance of air breathing targets, detection of cruise missiles, Unmanned Aerial Systems (UAS), rockets, artillery and mortars, and the cueing of air
 defense weapons. G/ATOR contributes to Littoral Operations in a Contested Environment and Expeditionary Advanced Base Operations through surveillance and detection of enemy air threats not seen by Navy
 sensors in the littorals, and by participating in a cooperative engagement network of sensors and shooters. G/ATOR enables Integrated Fire Control (IFC) and continues to assess and identify system changes
 necessary to support and engage fire on remote capability. G/ATOR surveillance coverage with IFC will provide unprecedented reach, volume, and precision in the execution of Operational Maneuver from the
 sea, allowing Naval forces to project and sustain power deep inland. G/ATOR is the primary Ground-Based sensor for the United States Marine Corps and is the only air defense/air surveillance radar currently in
 the Marine Corps inventory. G/ATOR's initial operational capability was achieved in FY 2018. With the addition of nine (9) Expeditionary Airfield Surveillance Radar (EASR) systems in FY 2023, the award of Full
 Rate Production Lot 6 procurement, and intermittent deliveries to the United States Air Force, Pacific Air Forces (PACAF), full operational capability will now be achieved in FY 2029.

 Multi-Domain Radar in a Contested Environment (MuDRaCE) provides detection and air surveillance in spectrum dense environments, without centralized high-power radio frequency emitters, allowing for
 Aviation and Ground Command Control agencies to minimize the probability of detection through signature management. The Medium Range Air Defense Radar (MRADR) is an expeditionary, trailer mounted
 passive radar and the first member of the MuDRaCE Family of Systems (FoS). MRADR addresses Integrated Air and Missile Defense (IAMD) gaps and aligns with the current National Defense Strategy. MRADR
 directly supports Force Design and is a Future Naval Capability (FNC) that transitioned from the Office of Naval Research (ONR) in FY 2023.




