INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1506_L051$$, 2027, $$F-35B Correction of Deficiencies provides near and long-term improvements to fielded F-35B jets and focuses on correcting documented deficiencies related to safety, maintainability, life limits, and aircraft
 systems. Funds are required to manage, prepare, process, and incorporate Engineering Change Proposals (ECP) to sustain and improve F-35B system operations. Artisans at the organic depot and contractor
 field teams perform the installation of these modifications and selected component changes into the Air System. To meet emerging deficiencies, the airframe and integrated systems require modifications to
 resolve the identified deficiencies.

 The major thrust under this OSIP is Structural Life Limited Parts deficiencies. The SLLP program focuses on resolving identified life limits up to 8,000 flight hours enabling the aircraft to meet full life. Currently,
 62 ECPs make up the F-35B SLLP program scope, requiring a retrofit solution to remove the life limit constraint. In FY2027, the Program will continue to conduct Non-Recurring Engineering to develop solutions
 to correct life limiting deficiencies. Additionally, the Program will procure and install material. The Program expects to continue additional Engineering Change Proposals (ECP) during analysis and through
 continued fleet operations.

 In FY2021 and continuing through the FYDP, Laser Shock Peening (LSP) stood-up at Fleet Readiness Center-East to resolve three ECPs on the F-35B aircraft. The three LSP ECPs are located on the FS-472
 Bulkhead (ECP-0735), FS-496 Bulkhead (ECP 0673), and the Wing Rear Spar (ECP 0268). LSP is a process where a unique high-energy laser is fired at an ablative material on the surface of a metal part
 to generate pressure pulses up to one million pounds per square inch, which send shock waves through the part. Multiple firings of the laser in a pre-defined surface pattern will impart a layer of residual
 compressive stress that is up to four times deeper than that attainable from conventional peening treatments. Deeper levels of compressive stress provide greater resistance to potential fatigue and corrosion
 failures. In FY2022, the program stood up LSP at Ogden Air Logistics Complex and began inducting F-35B aircraft.

 Under the SLLP Program, the F-35B has a unique set of life limiting structural deficiencies within the wing rear spar and Horizontal tail efforts. Early LRIP and later LOT aircraft have these deficiencies. The
 Program will continue to correct these deficiencies during FY2027. In FY2027, the program will continue to procure and install other SLLP modifications.

 SLLP material costs differences between first year and subsequent years is due to cost share agreements between the government and the prime contractor.

 JUSTIFICATION:
 Funding under this OSIP in FY2027 is also required to support Structural Life Limited Mods material, installation labor and associated support costs across two US organic Depots for F-35B inductions. This
 includes modifications management, depot installation support, and depot installation over and above activities. This includes supplementary actions necessary to safely return inducted aircraft to flight status
 prior to completing the modification event.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                                               Date: April 2026
