INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1506_L052$$, 2027, $$F-35C Correction of Deficiencies provides near and long-term improvements to fielded F-35C jets and focuses on correcting documented deficiencies related to safety, maintainability, life limits, and aircraft
 systems. Funds are required to manage, prepare, process and incorporate Engineering Change Proposals (ECP) to sustain and improve F-35C system operations. Artisans at the organic depot and contractor
 field teams perform the installation of these modifications and select component changes into the Air System. To meet emerging deficiencies, the airframe and integrated systems require modifications to resolve
 the identified deficiencies.

 The major thrust under this OSIP is Structural Life Limited Parts deficiencies. The SLLP program focuses on resolving identified life limits up to 8,000 flight hours enabling the aircraft to meet full life. Currently,
 98 ECPs make up the F-35C SLLP program scope, requiring a retrofit solution to remove the life limit constraint. In FY2027, the Program will continue to conduct Non-Recurring Engineering to develop solutions
 to correct life limiting deficiencies. Additionally, the Program will procure and install material. The Program expects to continue additional Engineering Change Proposals (ECP) during analysis and through
 continued fleet operations.

 In FY2021 and continuing through the FYDP, Laser Shock Peening (LSP) stood-up at Fleet Readiness Center-East to resolve an ECP located on the FS-496 Bulkhead (ECP-0690). LSP is a process where a
 unique high-energy laser is fired at an ablative material on the surface of a metal part to generate pressure pulses up to one million pounds per square inch, which send shock waves through the part. Multiple
 firings of the laser in a pre-defined surface pattern will impart a layer of residual compressive stress that is up to four times deeper than that attainable from conventional peening treatments. Deeper levels of
 compressive stress provide greater resistance to potential fatigue and corrosion failures. In FY2022, the program stood up LSP at Ogden Air Logistics Complex and began inducting F-35C aircraft.

 Under the SLLP Program, the F-35C has a unique set of life limiting structural deficiencies under the upper wing skin referred to as the CV Upper Wing Skin (UWS) effort. Early Low-Rate Initial Production (LRIP)
 aircraft have 29 of these deficiencies which decrease in subsequent LRIP and LOT aircraft as corrections get made in production aircraft. The Program plans to correct all these deficiencies during a single
 depot induction to eliminate the need to remove the wing skin more than once. The first of these inductions are planned for FY27 to prove out the modification kits, installation tooling, and instructions.

 SLLP material costs differences between first year and subsequent years are due to cost share agreements between the government and the prime contractor.

 JUSTIFICATION:
 Funding under this OSIP in FY2027 is also required to support Structural Life Limited Mods material, installation labor and associated support costs for F-35C modification inductions. This includes modifications
 management, depot site support, and depot over and above activities. This includes supplementary actions necessary to safely return inducted aircraft to flight status prior to completing the modification event.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                                          Date: April 2026
